// TEST: js_handling_let_redeclaration
// EXPECT: output "[first][second]"
// EXPECT: targets js, ts, python, rust
//
// Regression for Q-js-handling-let-redeclaration: a `let` re-bound under the
// SAME name in two *sibling* `handling { … }` blocks was dropped on the js/ts
// backends. Each `handling` block lowers to its own `{ … }` JS lexical scope,
// but the emitter never opened a fresh `let`-scope frame for it. The
// redeclaration tracker therefore carried the first block's `declared` set into
// the second block and rewrote its `let part = "second"` into a bare
// `part = "second"` — an assignment to a name that went out of scope when the
// first block closed. Under the harness's ESM (`{"type":"module"}`, strict)
// execution this throws `ReferenceError: part is not defined` on js, and `tsc`
// rejects the undeclared name (TS2304) on ts. The fix opens a fresh let-scope
// per `handling` block (mirroring the value-position block IIFE), so each
// sibling block declares its own block-scoped `const part`.
//
// The effect op `log` is genuinely invoked inside each block (it returns a
// `[…]`-tagged copy of its argument); the two results accumulate into `acc`,
// printed once with `println` so the harness's literal single-line
// `output "…"` comparison matches. js/ts/python/rust only: the Go backend
// (go.rs) carries the same block-scope defect (`part := …` in the first block,
// bare `part = …` in the second → `undefined: part`), tracked separately as a
// FOUND on go.rs; this fixture pins the js/ts fix (plus the already-correct
// python/rust backends). `main` is intentionally NOT `public` (Go entry-point
// rationale, see hello_world.bock).
module main

effect Log {
  fn log(message: String) -> String
}

record Tagger {}

impl Log for Tagger {
  fn log(message: String) -> String {
    "[${message}]"
  }
}

fn main() -> Void {
  let mut acc = ""
  handling (Log with Tagger {}) {
    let part = "first"
    acc = acc + log(part)
  }
  handling (Log with Tagger {}) {
    let part = "second"
    acc = acc + log(part)
  }
  println(acc)
}
